Time Limit: 1 sec
Memory: 256 MB

Description
Given two numbers N and M, a 2D array A of size N × M and a number X. Determine whether X exists in the 2D array A or not.

Input Format
First line contains an integer T, the number of test cases.
First line of each test case contains two integers N and M separated by a space.
Next N lines contain M space-separated integers.
Next line contains an integer X.

Output Format
Print will take number if the number doesn't exist in the 2D array otherwise, print will not take number.

Constraints
2 ≤ N, M ≤ 100
1 ≤ A[i][j] ≤ 10^5
0 ≤ X ≤ 10^5

Sample Input 1
1
2 2
1 2
3 4
3

Sample Output 1
will not take number

Sample Input 2
2
2 2
1 2
3 4
3
2 2
1 2
3 4
10

Sample Output 2
will not take number
will take number

Note

Sample Input 1:
We have a 2 × 2 matrix:
1 2
3 4

The number to search is X = 3, which exists in the matrix. Hence, we print "will not take number".

Sample Input 2:

First test case:
Matrix:
1 2
3 4

X = 3, which exists in the matrix. So, we print "will not take number".

Second test case:
Matrix:
1 2
3 4

X = 10, which does not exist in the matrix. So, we print "will take number".



#include<iostream>
typedef long long ll;
#include<bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;


int main()
{
    int t;
    cin>>t;
    while(t--)
    {
        int n,m;
        cin>>n>>m;
        int arr[n][m];
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        {
            for(int j = 0; j < m; j++)
            {
                cin>>arr[i][j];
            }
        }
        int x;
        cin>>x;
        bool flag = false;
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        {
            for(int j = 0; j < m; j++)
            {
                if(x == arr[i][j])
                {
                    flag = true;
                }
            }
        }
        if(!flag)
        {
            cout<<"will take number"<<endl;
        }else{
            cout<<"will not take number"<<endl;
        }
    }
}
